Url.Title: <ProductName> Web Application Developer Experience
Url.Abstract: Saleslogix Web Developer Experience Use the Application Architect to develop, customize, maintain, and deploy your Web applications.

Url.Title: JavaScript and VBScript
Url.Abstract: About JavaScript and VBScript Some JavaScript functions are stored in files outside of templates and referenced rather than incorporated into the template. These JavaScripts include global functions to aid in data management. Scripts used by Saleslogix portals are located under the SupportFiles\jscript folder of each portal. You can add or copy scripts to the same folder for use by your custom applications.

Url.Title: MySLX API
Url.Abstract: MySLX API MySLX is a library of shortcuts for commonly used objects, methods, and programming tasks. This release introduces the MySLX functionality and provides several initial utility methods. Feedback from our customers and business partners will guide the rapid evolution of this convenient and time-saving developer tool.

Url.Title: Saleslogix Event Handling in the Page Life Cycle
Url.Abstract: Saleslogix Event Handling in the Page Life Cycle Using Microsoft's familiar explanation of a page life cycle, this topic explains the expected Saleslogix behaviors at each stage.

Url.Title: About Client-Side Validation
Url.Abstract: About Client-Side Form Validation The Web Client runs form validation at the Save onClick event. Working in conjunction with the ClientBindingManagerService, the onClick event of each registered Save button uses Sage.Utility.Validate to cause the dijit-based controls in the containing workspace to run their validation. Normal entity navigation or any other asynchronous postbacks are not affected; validation is not run at this time. Also, individual controls continue to run their validation at the onBlur event.

Url.Title: Key CAB Concepts
Url.Abstract: Composite UI Application Block (CAB) The Saleslogix Web Client architecture uses Microsoft CAB objects. For example, it uses ObjectBuilder to implement the Builder and Dependency Injection patterns. Classes based on other CAB components are used to implement the other patterns in a platform-independent manner.

Url.Title: ObjectBuilder
Url.Abstract: ObjectBuilder The ObjectBuilder CAB provides a central framework for the creation, initialization, and management of objects in the Saleslogix application architecture. ObjectBuilder is made up of the following parts:

Url.Title: WorkItems
Url.Abstract: Work Items A WorkItem represents a unit of work in an application. It is a container for user interface elements and views, state, and services. Every CAB application contains a Root WorkItem that serves as the top level container for global services and the other application Work Items. The definition of the WorkItem class resides in the Sage.Platform.Application assembly.

Url.Title: Workspaces
Url.Abstract: Workspaces Workspaces are user interface containers for Smart Parts. The Saleslogix portal page template contains several predefined workspaces: MainContent, Tab, Dialog, ToolBar, and NavigationBar. The separation of Smart Parts from their WorkSpace containers allows the appearance of an application to be changed through configuration with the Application Architect. When you map a Smart Part to a page, you choose the WorkSpace with which the Smart Part will be associated and thus where on the page the Smart Part will appear.

Url.Title: Accessing a Page WorkItem from a Smart Part
Url.Abstract: Accessing a Page WorkItem from a Smart Part Quick forms have a page WorkItem property. For a custom Smart Part, use the Page WorkItem Locator service.

Url.Title: Using Automation Tools
Url.Abstract: Using Automation Tools The following automation tools are available for use with your Saleslogix Web applications. These command-line utilities are installed in the Saleslogix directory on the Administrative Workstation.

Url.Title: BundleDiff.exe
Url.Abstract: BundleDiff.exe The BundleDiff.exe finds differences between two bundle manifests. For example, to preview customizations that might require merging during an upgrade, you can use this utility to compare a Saleslogix difference bundle with your customization bundle.

Url.Title: bundler.exe
Url.Abstract: bundler.exe The bundler.exe creates a bundle of part or all of a project at the command prompt using one of the following methods:

Url.Title: FindOrphans.exe
Url.Abstract: FindOrphans.exe The Find Orphans utility identifies code snippet orphans that may exist in your code. You can use this utility to find code snippet orphans that you may want to delete. This can help resolve issues you may have building the code snippet library.

Url.Title: fscopy.exe
Url.Abstract: FSCopy.exe FSCopy.exe is a command-line utility that allows you to import or export between Saleslogix supported file system types (VFS, ZIP, disk). For information on the arguments of this utility, type the utility name at a command line prompt in the Saleslogix install directory on the Administrative Workstation.

Url.Title: modelutility.exe
Url.Abstract: ModelUtility.exe ModelUtility.exe automates command-line builds of the Sage.Entity.Interfaces.dll and the 'Web classes' of the associated implementation assemblies such as Sage.SalesLogix.Entities.dll. For information on the arguments of this utility, type the utility name at a command line prompt in the Saleslogix install directory on the Administrative Workstation.

Url.Title: About Sage Data (SData)
Url.Abstract: About Sage Data (SData) Sage Data (SData) provides a simple standard protocol for reading data from and writing data to business applications. Saleslogix desktop, server, and Web-based applications use it to communicate with each other, and also with third-party applications and the world wide web.

Url.Title: About Job Server
Url.Abstract: About the Job Server SUMMARY The Job Server enables you to schedule single and recurring tasks for immediate or delayed execution, either manually or dynamically at run time. It executes tasks out of process, freeing up worker threads and memory for client sessions. Good candidates for this are long running tasks and resource intensive tasks.

Url.Title: sparklines
Url.Abstract: Sparklines A sparkline is a small, high resolution graphic embedded in text. It can be used as a replacement for a number or a range of numbers.

Url.Title: HQL Queries - Supported Functions
Url.Abstract: Supported Functions for HQL Queries Saleslogix supports a variety of functions for your use in all HQL queries. Some typical situations in which Saleslogixdevelopers build NHibernate queries are for HQL Data Source controls, for Mashup Query processors, and in code snippets. See the Application Architect online Help topics "Hql Data Source Control", "HQL Processor Type", and "Using Quick Form Action Items".

Url.Title: SData - Supported Functions
Url.Abstract: Supported Functions for SData Queries Saleslogix supports the following functions in the SData specification for use in SData queries. Refer tohttp://interop.sage.com/daisy/sdata/AnatomyOfAnSDataURL/QueryLanguage for more information.

Url.Title: Customizing a <ProductName> Web Help Topic
Url.Abstract: Customizing a Saleslogix Web Help Topic If you have customized views in the Saleslogix (Web Client) portal or Saleslogix Customer portal, you may want to customize the content of the associated help topic.

Url.Title: Linking to Another Help Topic
Url.Abstract: Linking to Another Help Topic It is often helpful to link from one topic to another related help topic. Use the steps below to insert a link to another help topic.

Url.Title: Adding or Removing Images in a Help Topic
Url.Abstract: Adding or Removing Images in a Help Topic You can add images to a help topic to display a button or icon used in the Saleslogix Web interface.

Url.Title: Formatting Custom Web Help with help.css
Url.Abstract: Formatting Custom Web Help Formatting within Web help topics is controlled by classes and rules defined within a cascading style sheet file (.css). Class styles can be applied to HTML tags and allow you set style attributes for blocks of text. For more information about cascading style sheets and class styles and rules, refer to the help system in your editor of choice. The .css file used for the Saleslogix help topics is named SALESLOGIX.CSS and is located in the help\Content folder found under each Saleslogix Web portal.

Url.Title: Deleting Topics from a Project
Url.Abstract: Deleting Topics from a Project You can delete help topics that do not apply to your business. In addition to removing the topics, you should remove any links in the table of contents, index or other topics.

Url.Title: Creating a Custom Help Topic
Url.Abstract: Creating a Custom Help Topic The easiest way to create a new help topic is to copy and then modify the samplehelp.htm topic. This will ensure that the necessary formatting and required information are contained in the new file.

Url.Title: Adding Custom Help Topics to a Project
Url.Abstract: Adding Custom Help Topics to a Project The help is organized into topics and folders. Folders can be used to group related topics.

Url.Title: Adding a Help Topic Alias
Url.Abstract: Working with the Alias.xml In order to link a help topic to a help button, you must create an alias for the topic.

Url.Title: Include a Topic in the Index
Url.Abstract: Including a Topic in the Index After creating a custom topic, you can create an index entry for the topic so that it appears in the index.

Url.Title: Include a Topic in the TOC
Url.Abstract: Including a Topic in the Table of Contents After creating a custom topic, you can customize the table of contents so that the topic appears in the table of contents.

Url.Title: Linking a Help Topic to a Help Button
Url.Abstract: Linking a Help Topic to a Help Button You can create a custom help topic for a custom form or Quick Form and link it to a help button so that it looks like any other Saleslogix Web view.

Url.Title: Upgrading Customized Help
Url.Abstract: Upgrading Customized Help When upgrading from v7.5.2 and later your customizations will be captured in the bundle process. However, when upgrading from v7.5.0 or v7.5.1 you must recreate your customizations in the new help topics.

Url.Title: Adding Conditions to Lookups in <PortalCustomer>
Url.Abstract: Adding Conditions to Lookups in Customer Portal You can narrow the scope of lookups on an entity in the Saleslogix Customer portal by adding a condition in the appSettings.config file.

Url.Title: Adding Contextual Awareness for Custom Entity Main Views
Url.Abstract: Adding Contextual Awareness for Custom Entity Main Views When users navigate from one main view to another, the current group list must be re-built based on the page the user navigated from. The rules about this contextual awareness are specified by entity in the ContextualListConfiguration.xml file for the portal. To add contextual awareness for navigating to and from custom entity main views, add them to the ContextualListConfiguration.xml file.

Url.Title: Adding Culture to List in Form Designer
Url.Abstract: Adding a Culture to List in the Form Designer The Form Designer in the Saleslogix Web Client has a Culture drop-down list which displays a static list of cultures. You can add to the list by editing the base.master file.

Url.Title: Adding a Custom Entity to a Merge Business Rule
Url.Abstract: Adding a Custom Entity to a Merge Business Rule The merge functionality in the Saleslogix Web Client is handled by calling merge business rules. These business rules use post execute steps to move child records from the source parent to the target parent after the merge. You can add a custom child entity to the merge process by adding a post execute step to update its parent entity.

Url.Title: Adding File Types for Attachments
Url.Abstract: Adding File Types for Attachments When users open an attachment, their browser uses the MIME type of the attachment to determine what player or application to use. If you want to add or change attachment MIME types for your installation, you must edit the web.config file for each portal that supports attachments. In the base product, SlxClient and SLXCustomerPortal support attachments.

Url.Title: Applying Action Security to Custom Forms
Url.Abstract: Applying Action Security to Custom Forms Action Security is a way to control access to the functionality of user interface elements by user role. Refer to "Understanding Secured Actions" in the Application Architect online Help for an overview of the feature.

Url.Title: Applying Field Level Security to Entity Insertion
Url.Abstract: Applying Field Level Security to Entity Insertion Field Level Security, by default, does not apply to insertion of new entities. Take for example a user whose Field Level Security specifies no access to the CreditRating property of the Account entity. The user can set the CreditRating property during the insert of a new Account. After the insert, the user cannot change or read the property.

Url.Title: Changing the Active Tab and Captions on a MultiTab Control
Url.Abstract: Setting the Active Tab and Captions on a MultiTab Control On a MultiTab control, the user can click a tab to set the visible page, or you can set the visible page through code. The following examples show how to set some Multitab properties through code. The first example explains how to set the active tab, and the second example shows how the captions are dynamically updated to the opportunity description and the account name.

Url.Title: Changing Logo in <PortalPrimary>
Url.Abstract: Changing the Logo in the Saleslogix (Web Client) portal You can replace the Saleslogix logo image used in the Web Client or point it to a different image. The default logo is 134 x 23 pixels. If you are using a different image size, review the client screens for any impact to their layouts.

Url.Title: Configuring the <ProductName> Cache Server
Url.Abstract: Configuring the Saleslogix Cache Server The Saleslogix Cache Server is used to store Web data which allows the cache to be real-time. By default, the Saleslogix Cache Server is installed on the Web Host. If you install the Saleslogix Cache Server on a server other than the Web Host, you must update the web.config file to include the location of the Saleslogix Cache Server.

Url.Title: Consuming SData through the Web Client
Url.Abstract: Consuming SData through the Web Client When writing Web Client customizations that consume SData feeds, you can access the feeds directly through the Saleslogix (Web Client) portal so that it handles authentication. Url.Title: Creating custom controls for quick forms
Url.Abstract: Creating Custom Controls for Quick Forms You can create custom controls and use them in Application Architect Quick Forms.

Url.Title: Creating a Custom Mashup Processor
Url.Abstract: Creating a Custom Mashup Processor Processors are controls that you add to mashups. You can use the ones provided as well as create custom processors.

Url.Title: Customizing the Move Contact Process
Url.Abstract: Customizing the Move Contact Process The Move Contact process provides several opportunities for customization.

Url.Title: Customizing the Whats New Module
Url.Abstract: Customizing the What's New Module You can customize the tabs on the What's New page by configuring an XML file. When the What's New module is executed within the page, it looks for the existence of WhatsNew_Config.xml in the App_Data folder of the portal. If it exists, the rendering logic changes and uses the details contained within to determine the smart parts that get displayed. A sample configuration file, WhatsNew_Config_Example.xml, is provided. The easiest way to configure the file is to deploy your Saleslogix (Web Client) portal, copy or rename the resultant file to WhatsNew_Config.xml, and edit it in Visual Studio. When you have completed your changes in Visual Studio, copy the updated file back into the SupportFiles\App_Data folder in your project.

Url.Title: Editing Configuration Files
Url.Abstract: Editing Configuration Files The web.config and appSettings.config files (associated with ASP.NET) act as containers for settings that describe how the ASP.NET-specific portions of the application should be handled.

Url.Title: Enabling Check for Duplicates for an Entity
Url.Abstract: Enabling Check for Duplicates for an Entity The Check for Duplicates wizard in the Saleslogix Web Client checks for duplicate accounts, contacts, and leads. This help topic explains how to add other entities including custom entities to the wizard.

Url.Title: Enabling Debug Logging for Business Rules
Url.Abstract: Enabling Debug Logging for Business Rules To debug business rules in Visual Studio, you can enable logging in the log4net.config file.

Url.Title: Exposing Tabs When a Page Loads
Url.Abstract: Exposing Tabs on Page Load When a page loads, the tabs are exposed based on the active tab and the remembered tab state. To make a particular tab visible, use one of the following methods according to how the page will be accessed:

The following example shows how to use the schema to detect the property type and format the property value based on the current culture. The sample code uses the SData Core Client Libraries which are available with documentation and examples at https://github.com/Saleslogix/SDataCSharpClientLib.

Url.Title: Hiding/Unhiding a Tab at run time
Url.Abstract: Hiding/Unhiding a Tab at Run Time You can hide and unhide a tab using code in a page module. The portal page loads modules as one of the last parts of the page creation process. Using a custom module to set the hidden flag on a tab and placing it after the other modules will ensure that the change is the last one executed.

Url.Title: Improving Performance of Custom JavaScript
Url.Abstract: Improving Performance of Custom JavaScript The Saleslogix common scripts are minified and merged during the build process into Sage-common.js (or sage-common-debug.js) in order to reduce the number of http requests to the server.

Url.Title: Linking to Entity Views with JavaScript
Url.Abstract: Linking to Entity Views with JavaScript Most entity details are rendered in a main view. However, a few entities such as Activities and ActivityHistory load in a dialog box. Thus, when you build a URL to redirect to entity detail pages, you must change the URL pattern depending on the entity type.

Url.Title: Loading Multiple Versions of JQuery
Url.Abstract: Loading Multiple Versions of jQuery You can load multiple versions of jQuery by using the noConflict function. For more information on the function, see http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.noConflict/.

Url.Title: Localizing Strings in Client-Side Code
Url.Abstract: Localizing Strings in Client-Side Code Several quick form properties accept JavaScript functions. You can make strings used by such JavaScript functions localizable. For more information, refer to Client Resource Keys collection editor. See "Client Resource Keys Collection Editor" in the Application Architect online Help..

Url.Title: Modifying Job Notification Visibility
Url.Abstract: Modifying Job Notification Visibility The Job Manager provides a user interface for creating and managing the jobs sent to the Saleslogix Job Server. Job Server is an engine for processing single and\or recurring tasks for immediate or delayed execution. The Job Server is a shared service that can be consumed by any Saleslogix client, including Web, Windows, and Mobile. There are 9 threads to the Job Server, enabling multiple jobs to run at one time.

Url.Title: Redirecting Web Client Logoff Timeout
Url.Abstract: Redirecting Web Client Logoff/Timeout By default, the Saleslogix Web Client redirects to the logoff.aspx page when it times out or logs off. You can edit the appSettings.config file to redirect to another page.

Url.Title: Registering Scripts Dynamically
Url.Abstract: Registering Scripts Dynamically Register scripts with the ScriptManager according to the following instructions to enable them to work correctly with AJAX update panels.

Url.Title: Setting the Maximum File Size for the Web Client
Url.Abstract: Setting the Maximum File Upload Size for Web Applications You can alter the maximum size of files uploaded to the Saleslogix Web Client. The default size is 4MB.

Url.Title: Setting Potential Match Indexing Options
Url.Abstract: Setting Potential Match Indexing Options The Potential Match Service is used during lead import to find potential matches for the lead being imported and to prevent duplicates in the system. You can set options that specify what situations require a Potential Match Index update.

Url.Title: Troubleshooting Data Binding Errors
Url.Abstract: Troubleshooting Data Binding Errors In Application Architect, the data binding editor attempts to validate data binding elements as you set them. However, since there are some things it cannot evaluate until run time, it may generate breaking data binding elements. To see data binding errors that happen at run time, turn on the ShowBindingErrorsAtRuntime flag in the appSettings.config file for the portal. This visibility can be particularly useful when debugging custom smart parts.

Url.Title: Using the Global CSS Image Sprite
Url.Abstract: Using the Global CSS Image Sprite Saleslogix uses an image sprite to reduce the number of server requests for icons. User interface elements created with Application Architect use the icons by automatically referencing the appropriate sections of the sprite. Customizations can also use the global image sprite to reduce server requests.

Url.Abstract: Working With Static versus Dynamic Entities through Code Each static entity has an interface with well-defined properties. Since dynamic entities do not, they must be manipulated with strings and dictionaries. If you reflect on an entity class to see its list of properties, you cannot see dynamic properties in the list. Url.Title: Understanding Process Orchestration
Url.Abstract: Understanding Process Orchestration Process Orchestration functionality permits you to control the flow of work in Saleslogix. Process Orchestration workflows can be bound to any kind of Saleslogix entity.

Url.Title: Implementing Process Orchestration
Url.Abstract: Implementing Process Orchestration Implementing Process Orchestration involves the following basic tasks:

Url.Title: Installing <ProductName> VS Workflow Items
Url.Abstract: Installing Saleslogix VS Workflow Items The Saleslogix Visual Studio Workflow Extensions is a set of tools for creating Saleslogix-specific Windows Workflows.

Url.Title: Building Custom Workflows
Url.Abstract: Building Custom Workflows Use Visual Studio Workflow Designer to create workflows. Use any mix of Windows Workflow activities, Saleslogix custom activities, and activities you create. You can bind your workflow to any Saleslogix entity.

Url.Title: Creating Security Entities
Url.Abstract: Creating Security Entities Create generated entities you can use when you create policy activities.

Url.Title: Using Policy Activities
Url.Abstract: Using Policy Activities Policy activities in Windows Workflow allow a workflow designer to set up complex business rules based on conditions and actions.

Url.Title: Understanding Goal Driven Workflows
Url.Abstract: Understanding Goal-Driven Workflows A goal-driven workflow is similar to a traditional state machine workflow, except it is less restrictive in its approach to moving between states. This approach can be used to provide process guidance and report, without forcing users to complete a set of steps in a particular order.

Url.Title: Registering Custom Workflows with the ProcessHost
Url.Abstract: Registering Custom Workflows with the ProcessHost After you build custom workflows and set up the Process Host portal, you can register the workflows with it.

Url.Title: Starting Workflows with Database Events
Url.Abstract: Starting Workflows Through Database Eventing Starting a workflow is equivalent to instantiating a workflow for a particular entity instance. You can configure a workflow to start in response to a database event such as the addition, change, or deletion of an entity. You can also set pre-conditions for the Process Orchestration run time to verify before running a process.

Url.Title: Enabling the Process Tasks Tasklet
Url.Abstract: Enabling the Process Tasks Tasklet The Process Tasks Tasklet permits users to mark goal-driven workflow items as complete in the Saleslogix Web Client. The tasklet is available in the Saleslogix (Web Client) portal by default, but it must be configured for it to show on entity Detail views in the Web Client.

Url.Title: Why SData Might be Turned Off
Url.Abstract: Why Would SData be Turned Off? Some Saleslogix entities have their SData feed turned on by default. You can turn the SData feed for an entity on or off on the SData tab when you edit the entity.

Url.Title: ContextualListConfiguration.xml file
Url.Abstract: ContextualListConfiguration.xml File When users navigate from one main view to another, the current group list must be re-built based on the page the user navigated from. The rules about this contextual awareness are specified by entity in the ContextualListConfiguration.xml file for the portal. It has the information needed by the group classes to build up the condition for the lookup results group. For each entity's main view, there is a <TargetConfigInfo> section that defines the conditions based on the <ReferingPages>.

Url.Title: Minify
Url.Abstract: Minify The process of reducing the number of characters in a file of code. Reducing the size of a java script file improves the performance of the page that uses it. There are utilities available that will strip out extra blanks and special characters such as line feeds, remove comments, and shorten variable names.

Url.Title: Pre-Conditions in Process Orchestration
Url.Abstract: Pre-Conditions in Process Orchestration The database eventing mechanism notifies the Process Orchestration engine that an entity instance has been changed, inserted, or deleted. After that, the process can run right away or evaluate conditions on the entity instance to determine if the process should run. For example, database eventing could fire when the Division property of an Account changes, and then the Process Host engine would start the process only if Account.State equals 'AZ' .
